## Data Flow Architecture for Handwriting Recognition in Tldraw Obsidian

This document describes how handwritten strokes drawn inside the **tldraw canvas integrated in Obsidian** move through the recognition system and eventually become searchable text inside the vault.

The goal is to transform handwritten vector strokes into indexed text without modifying the underlying drawing engine.

---

# System Overview

The recognition system sits **on top of the existing Tldraw plugin** as an observer layer.

It listens to editor events, extracts stroke geometry, processes handwriting recognition, and stores results in the markdown document.

High-level pipeline:

```id="g6f7h0"
User draws handwriting
      │
      ▼
Tldraw canvas editor
      │
      ▼
Shape created (type: draw)
      │
      ▼
Editor store update
      │
      ▼
Stroke listener
      │
      ▼
Stroke extraction
      │
      ▼
Stroke normalization
      │
      ▼
Stroke grouping
      │
      ▼
Handwriting recognizer
      │
      ▼
Recognized text
      │
      ▼
Index written to markdown
      │
      ▼
Obsidian search index
```

---

# Stage 1 — Canvas Input

Handwriting begins when the user draws using the **freehand draw tool**.

Each continuous pen stroke produces a new shape in the editor:

```id="dpxa7g"
shape.type = "draw"
```

Each shape contains vector stroke data.

Example structure:

```id="ujg5l4"
shape
 ├─ id
 ├─ x
 ├─ y
 └─ props
     └─ segments
          └─ points[]
```

Points represent the pen trajectory.

Example point:

```id="vck6dq"
{
  x: number
  y: number
  z: number
}
```

Where:

```id="rxr1sh"
x → horizontal movement
y → vertical movement
z → pressure
```

---

# Stage 2 — Store Event

The editor maintains all state inside a reactive store.

Whenever shapes change, the store emits an update event.

The handwriting system subscribes to:

```id="zj6wff"
editor.store.listen()
```

When a new draw shape appears, the system triggers stroke processing.

Recognition is performed only when:

```id="m6oajh"
shape.props.isComplete === true
```

This prevents processing incomplete strokes.

---

# Stage 3 — Stroke Extraction

The listener extracts raw stroke points from the shape.

Example extraction process:

```id="q2g41v"
shape.props.segments
   → segment.points
      → [x,y] coordinates
```

Result:

```id="g2bh8b"
stroke = [
  [x1,y1],
  [x2,y2],
  [x3,y3]
]
```

Multiple segments are merged into a single stroke representation.

---

# Stage 4 — Stroke Normalization

Raw strokes can contain hundreds of points.

Before recognition they should be normalized.

Normalization steps include:

### Resampling

Reduce stroke complexity.

Example:

```id="t5w8rf"
original points: 200
normalized points: 64
```

---

### Scaling

Normalize stroke size to a standard range.

Example:

```id="35l0r3"
0 ≤ x ≤ 1
0 ≤ y ≤ 1
```

---

### Translation

Shift stroke origin to:

```id="w8vdc9"
(0,0)
```

This removes dependency on canvas position.

---

# Stage 5 — Stroke Grouping

Individual strokes often represent letters rather than full words.

Example:

```id="p7g2zt"
h + e + l + l + o
```

Each letter may be drawn as a separate stroke.

Grouping logic merges nearby strokes into word candidates.

Grouping criteria:

### Temporal proximity

```id="04fov4"
time difference < 800 ms
```

---

### Spatial proximity

```id="cptm4t"
horizontal distance < threshold
```

Grouped strokes form a **word candidate**.

Example:

```id="y3n3eh"
{
 strokes: [stroke1, stroke2, stroke3],
 boundingBox: {...}
}
```

---

# Stage 6 — Recognition

Grouped strokes are passed to a handwriting recognition engine.

Possible engines include:

* Google ML Kit Digital Ink Recognition
* MyScript iink SDK

Recognizer input example:

```json id="ew1l0b"
{
 "strokes": [
   [
     {"x":0,"y":0,"t":0},
     {"x":1,"y":2,"t":1}
   ]
 ]
}
```

Recognizer output:

```json id="7y9y3n"
{
 "text": "hello",
 "confidence": 0.94
}
```

---

# Stage 7 — Index Generation

Recognized text is converted into a searchable index.

Example index entry:

```id="ujm0l3"
{
 word: "hello",
 shapeIds: ["shape1","shape2","shape3"],
 boundingBox: {...}
}
```

This index allows the system to map text results back to canvas positions.

---

# Stage 8 — Markdown Storage

Recognition results must persist across sessions.

The plugin stores recognition metadata inside the markdown document.

Example:

```id="b3n8y4"
<!-- tldraw-handwriting-index
shape:iQzNB4HB6nUwBK4hMf0p1 = "a"
shape:q6IgmlC3Z7JnfaGPiUXlv = "b"
shape:94zqqtdzWw3reavN9eSXr = "c"
-->
```

Because this text is inside the markdown file, **Obsidian automatically indexes it**.

---

# Stage 9 — Search Integration

When the user searches inside Obsidian:

```id="3y1i5f"
search query
      │
      ▼
markdown index
      │
      ▼
recognized handwriting entry
      │
      ▼
shape id retrieved
      │
      ▼
canvas navigation
```

The editor can move the viewport to the relevant location.

Example:

```id="h4n7ad"
editor.setCamera()
```

---

# Stage 10 — Canvas Navigation

Once a search result is selected:

```id="c7dmy8"
retrieve bounding box
      │
      ▼
zoom canvas
      │
      ▼
highlight strokes
```

This allows users to jump directly to handwritten content.

